nd regime. Thesis strength remains PLAUSIBLE rather than PROVEN because: (a) the backwardation signal is genuinely unresolved; (b) weather tail risk is real; (c) the 9+ month forward supply thesis leaves room for intervening disruptions; (d) multiple agent self-critiques acknowledge their own confidence limitations; (e) the consensus strength is only 0.51, reflecting genuine disagreement. [Consensus DIVERGENT (Master=BEARISH, Vote=BULLISH) → reduced size]", 'regime': 'RANGE_BOUND', 'volatility_sentiment': 'NEUTRAL', 'confidence': 0.56, 'price': 278.05, 'sma_200': 319.652, 'expected_price': 278.05, 'predicted_return': 0.0, 'thesis_strength': 'PLAUSIBLE', 'conviction_multiplier': 0.7}, {'contract_month': '202609', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'BEARISH', 'reason': "The debate turns on whether logistical disruption catalysts (Strait of Hormuz closure, Port of Santos congestion, carrier booking suspensions) are sufficient to override an increasingly well-documented supply surplus. After weighing evidence quality and independence, the bearish case holds more structural weight, though with meaningful uncertainty that prevents a 'PROVEN' designation.\n\nBEARISH EVIDENCE STACK (multiple independent lines):\n1. INVENTORY: ICE-certified Arabica stocks built from 435,494 to 477,229 bags over just 9 days (CocoaIntel, Feb 18-27). This is the most damning single data point — an accelerating physical inventory build DURING the period of alleged supply disruption directly falsifies the claim that disruptions are producing tightness.\n2. EXPORTS: Brazilian February 2026 exports +30.2% YoY (2,322,217 bags, Cecafé) and ICO January 2026 global exports +13.7% YoY (12.62M bags) — the supply pipeline is active and expanding, not contracting.\n3. CROP FUNDAMENTALS: Somar confirms 78mm rainfall at 131% of historical average (2026-03-03), consolidating bumper crop prospects. Conab projects 66.2M bags (+17.2% YoY). Multiple independent sources corroborate the supply surplus t